Great — now we’ll go deep + practical so you can reproduce, control, and fix plan regression both:
	•	✅ In AWS using Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL
	•	✅ On-prem using PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, and Oracle Database

⸻

🧪 PART 1 — AWS RDS POSTGRES CONFIG (MANUAL - CONSOLE)

⸻

🔹 STEP 1: Create Custom Parameter Group

Go to:

👉 RDS → Parameter Groups → Create

Settings:
	•	Family: postgres15 (or your version)
	•	Name: fintech-pg-tuning

⸻

🔹 STEP 2: Modify Parameters

Set these:

Parameter	Value	Why
autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor	0.02	Avoid sudden stats jumps
autovacuum_analyze_threshold	50	More frequent smaller updates
default_statistics_target	500	Better histograms
random_page_cost	1.1	Better index usage
effective_cache_size	75% of RAM	Better planner decisions


⸻

🔹 STEP 3: Attach to DB
	•	Modify DB instance
	•	Select parameter group
	•	Reboot DB

⸻

🧪 TEST SCENARIO (VERY IMPORTANT)

⸻

Create skewed table

CREATE TABLE orders (
  id serial PRIMARY KEY,
  status text,
  amount int
);

-- skewed data
INSERT INTO orders (status, amount)
SELECT 
  CASE WHEN random() < 0.95 THEN 'COMMON' ELSE 'RARE' END,
  (random()*1000)::int
FROM generate_series(1, 1000000);


⸻

Create index

CREATE INDEX idx_status ON orders(status);


⸻

Run query

EXPLAIN ANALYZE
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status = 'RARE';


⸻

Force bad stats

ANALYZE orders;

👉 Observe:
	•	Plan may switch (index → seq scan)

⸻

Fix with higher stats

ALTER TABLE orders ALTER COLUMN status SET STATISTICS 1000;
ANALYZE orders;

👉 Plan improves

⸻

🧱 PART 2 — TERRAFORM CONFIG (RDS PARAMETER GROUP)

⸻


resource "aws_db_parameter_group" "pg_tuning" {
  name   = "fintech-pg-tuning"
  family = "postgres15"

  parameter {
    name  = "autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor"
    value = "0.02"
  }

  parameter {
    name  = "autovacuum_analyze_threshold"
    value = "50"
  }

  parameter {
    name  = "default_statistics_target"
    value = "500"
  }

  parameter {
    name  = "random_page_cost"
    value = "1.1"
  }
}


⸻

Attach to RDS

resource "aws_db_instance" "postgres" {
  engine               = "postgres"
  instance_class       = "db.t3.medium"
  parameter_group_name = aws_db_parameter_group.pg_tuning.name
}


⸻

🧠 PART 3 — UNIVERSAL SOLUTION (ALL DATABASES)

⸻

🟦 A. FOR Microsoft SQL Server

⸻

🔴 Problem:
	•	Auto update stats → plan regression

⸻

✅ Solution:

1. Disable auto stats (selectively)

ALTER DATABASE db SET AUTO_UPDATE_STATISTICS OFF;


⸻

2. Use async stats

ALTER DATABASE db SET AUTO_UPDATE_STATISTICS_ASYNC ON;


⸻

3. Use Query Store (BEST)

ALTER DATABASE db SET QUERY_STORE = ON;

👉 Force good plan:

EXEC sp_query_store_force_plan @query_id, @plan_id;


⸻

4. Scheduled stats update

UPDATE STATISTICS orders WITH FULLSCAN;

👉 Run during low traffic

⸻

🟥 B. FOR Oracle Database

⸻

🔴 Problem:
	•	Optimizer picks bad plan after stats gather

⸻

✅ Solution:

⸻

1. Lock stats (CRITICAL TABLES)

EXEC DBMS_STATS.LOCK_TABLE_STATS('SCHEMA','ORDERS');


⸻

2. Use SQL Plan Baselines (BEST)

EXEC DBMS_SPM.LOAD_PLANS_FROM_CURSOR_CACHE;

👉 Prevents bad plan usage

⸻

3. Control stats gathering

EXEC DBMS_STATS.GATHER_TABLE_STATS(
  ownname => 'SCHEMA',
  tabname => 'ORDERS',
  estimate_percent => 100
);


⸻

🟩 C. FOR PostgreSQL (ON-PREM)

⸻

🔴 Problem:
	•	ANALYZE changes plan

⸻

✅ Solution:

⸻

1. Fine-tune autovacuum

ALTER TABLE orders SET (
  autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.02
);


⸻

2. Increase stats

ALTER TABLE orders ALTER COLUMN status SET STATISTICS 1000;


⸻

3. Extended stats

CREATE STATISTICS s1 (dependencies)
ON col1, col2 FROM orders;


⸻

4. Controlled ANALYZE

ANALYZE orders;

👉 Only during maintenance window

⸻

5. pg_hint_plan (optional)

Force plan if needed

⸻

